  "body": "View this post on the web at https://claireberlinski.substack.com/p/wine-under-the-bridge-protestant\r\n\r\nIf you missed it, here was the invitation to ask me anything [ https://substack.com/redirect/bfd029d8-515a-480b-8816-79a9334a7679?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ], and this was my first batch of replies. [ https://substack.com/redirect/329176a5-c682-431a-a9a2-ca952c01ac69?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/329176a5-c682-431a-a9a2-ca952c01ac69?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ](Some of the questions were simple enough for me to reply directly in the comment section.) \r\nI was determined to answer every question by the end of the weekend, so as you can imagine, I wrote in haste: Please forgive the odd typo. More importantly, if you don’t see an answer to your question, it is not a slight. It’s a mistake, owed to haste. Remind me in the comments. I meant to offer a serious answer to every question I was asked, and I think I did—but if I’m wrong, tell me.\r\nThere are three related questions, at the end, that I’ve decided to separate out and send separately. Perhaps I’ll even wait until tomorrow to send them. These questions vex me, and having labored at length to answer them, I don’t want my answers to be overlooked, which they might be owing to the length of this newsletter. \r\nBut I’ve finished answering all of the questions, I think. I had a very productive weekend, and I’m grateful to you for inspiring it. I feel much better. \r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Which wine would you pair with oysters, under the bridge?\r\n—Jake Ivry [ https://substack.com/profile/103121575-jake-ivry?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\nJake, I’d pair it wish a Muscadet Sèvre-et-Maine sur lie from the Loire. \r\nNow, it could be tricky getting it ice-cold, as it ought to be, under that bridge. Depends on the weather. It needs to be served at arctic temperatures, so if it’s warm out, I’ll have to scrounge up a bag of ice. \r\nBut this is the canonical oyster wine for a reason—high acidity, a faint saline-mineral note, no oak, no perfume, no vanity. When you’re living under a bridge, you’re not in the mood for trendy experiments. It’s also cheap, which matters when you’re living under a bridge. This bottle can be had for  [ https://substack.com/redirect/a5f2ddbd-d777-402c-9d22-973e554ca9ef?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]4.99€ at Monoprix [ https://substack.com/redirect/a5f2ddbd-d777-402c-9d22-973e554ca9ef?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ], for example, and it’s actually pretty drinkable:\r\n(Mind you, I don’t like oysters: I can never escape the thought that I’m eating a bunch of eyeballs. So I’d probably just stick with the wine, which would make the whole meal quite reasonable, financially speaking.) \r\nBuy me a bottle of Muscadet Sèvre-et-Maine sur lie:\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Stretching the guidelines just a little, I read an article a while ago concerning “The Roots of Political Violence in America” by Andrew Doran. The author’s theme involved an analysis of contemporaries, viz., John Brown and Orestes Brownson. A portion: \r\nBrownson also anticipated Polish philosopher Ryszard Legutko’s ‘totalitarian democracy’ thesis, set forth in The Demon in Democracy. Legutko argues that modern ideologies have a ‘humanistic-anthropological’ foundation, grounded in religious sentiment, and that democratic societies have the same potential to turn totalitarian that nondemocratic societies have.\r\nMost saliently, Brownson foresaw that social justice movements wouldn’t cease with the abolition of slavery but would “agitate” next for equality of the sexes, and that confusion would arise as egalitarian sentiment “obliterated all distinction of sex in politics, in social, industrial, and domestic arrangements.” After that, the activist “must go farther,” for there was “no limit to his agitation.” Ultimately, the social activist-ideologue “must regard creation itself as a blunder.” There would be no deference to Nature, depraved as it was: humanity would be malleable, perfectible, redeemed by and subordinate to human will and whim.\r\nThe First Great Awakening emphasized spiritual individualism—a personal relationship with God—but did so within the framework of mainline Protestant churches, most of which were bound in some way to national governments in Europe, thereby linking the American colonies to Europe. The Second Great Awakening came soon after America severed political and ecclesial bonds with Europe, at a time when the spirit of democratic individualism was going west, into the frontier, starting in upstate New York. There, ideology began to replace theology, religious passion merged with politics, and revivals were succeeded by social reform movements.\r\nRelevant, salient or all wet? I’ll post the article if necessary. Thanks again.\r\n—Russell-Dad Whiting [ https://substack.com/profile/6268785-russell-dad-whiting?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\nI believe this is the article you have in mind, Russell? The Roots of our Political Violence? [ https://substack.com/redirect/fcc4e4fe-b2ef-44d8-8760-fe5be443ef65?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/fcc4e4fe-b2ef-44d8-8760-fe5be443ef65?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]Relevant, yes; salient, partly; all wet, no—but very overstated. Not worthless, but overstated in ways that matters.\r\nThe article is good and original, but what’s good isn’t original, and what’s original isn’t good. The good part is the familiar but important observation that American reform politics has often drawn on Protestant revivalist energies, especially in the nineteenth century. The original part is Doran’s effort to inflate this into a grand, monocausal theory of American political pathology—a sweeping genealogy of modern progressivism as quasi-Gnostic, proto-totalitarian revolt against nature. That’s much less persuasive. \r\nIt is absolutely true that American reform movements tend to draw on Protestant revivalist energies. The Second Great Awakening, the Burned-over District, abolitionism, temperance, women’s rights, perfectionism, millenarian sects, communitarian experiments, spiritualism, Mormonism, Adventism—all draw or drew from the same religious and emotional reservoir. So if the question is, “Is there something about American political culture that repeatedly turns politics into moral crusades?” then yes. Absolutely. That’s salient.\r\nBut Doran isn’t just saying, “American politics reflects this Protestant moral intensity.” He is saying something more like, “Modern progressivism is a post-Christian, quasi-Gnostic, Puritan political religion whose logic runs from abolitionism through social justice to metaphysical rebellion against nature, and ultimately to violence.” And that argument is tendentious. It treats very different movements—abolitionism, feminism, contemporary social justice activism—as if they were stages in one unfolding metaphysical disease. History is far more complicated than that. \r\nIt’s absolutely true that the United States has never been a fully secular political culture in the European sense. (And neither has Europe, really:  [ https://substack.com/redirect/ed08839d-4906-4a62-93d6-957d18f7d457?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]It’s just buried religion a bit deeper [ https://substack.com/redirect/ed08839d-4906-4a62-93d6-957d18f7d457?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ].) American politics has always absorbed religious longings—you repeatedly see the themes of covenant, chosenness, jeremiad, redemption, apocalypse, purification, national mission. The Burned-over District really did produce a dense thicket of reform movements and religious experiments. It’s perfectly fair to say that the moral imagination of evangelical Protestantism shaped abolitionism and other nineteenth-century reform causes. It’s also fair to say that American politics often turns policy disputes into dramas of sin, redemption, and damnation. \r\nBut the fact that abolitionism and the movement for women’s rights emerged partly from revivalist reform culture doesn’t mean they were pathological. Abolitionism was morally correct. Women’s rights were morally correct. The presence of religious intensity around a cause tells us something about its style, not its truth value. That’s the article’s sleight of hand: It treats fervor as evidence of fanaticism, and fanaticism as evidence against the cause. But some injustices deserve fervor. Slavery wasn’t a minor administrative defect in the republic. It was a monstrous institution. Those who failed to be morally inflamed by slavery were morally defective.\r\nJohn Brown is a harder case. He really was violent and millenarian. He really did help precipitate the Civil War. But to make Brown the hidden ancestor of modern progressivism is a polemical flourish, not an argument. Brown is noteworthy precisely because most abolitionists didn’t become John Brown. \r\nIf you want to explain political violence in America, you can’t just trace a line from revivalism to abolitionism to contemporary progressivism. You have consider slavery itself, white supremacist violence, frontier violence, anti-Catholic violence, labor violence, nativist violence, lynching, paramilitary groups, anarchism, state violence, and the myth of redemptive violence across the American political spectrum—which has many intellectual forefathers. And you have to consider nihilism, too: Hardly a Protestant sentiment. As I wrote here, there’s an eerie similarity between America’s culture of mass shootings and the sinister and contagious form of violent nihilism that emerged between 1861 and 1866 in Russia:\r\nOrestes Brownson is an interesting figure, and his suspicion that humanitarian reform could become a substitute religion isn’t trivial. There’s a serious conservative insight there: Modern politics can become soteriological. Once politics promises redemption, it easily becomes coercive, because anyone standing between humanity and salvation becomes not a political opponent but an obstacle to be removed.\r\nBut this idea has to be handled carefully. Brownson opposed slavery, but he also feared the radical implications of egalitarianism. His anxiety about “obliterating all distinction of sex” isn’t prophecy in some simple sense; it’s also nineteenth-century conservative alarm at women’s emancipation. That controversies over sex and gender make Brownson sound “prescient” to Doran doesn’t mean his whole theory was right. You can oppose utopianism without treating every expansion of equality as a revolt against creation. \r\nSimilarly, his invocation of Legutko. The Demon in Democracy is a polemic against liberal-democratic modernity. There are some perceptive observations there about conformism in liberal societies in that book, but its totalitarian-democracy thesis is much too broad. Liberal democracies can become illiberal, censorious, and morally self-intoxicated. But saying they therefore have the “same” totalitarian potential as undemocratic societies flattens distinctions that matter enormously. \r\nThe word “Gnostic” is also doing too much work. Calling modern progressivism “Gnostic” has become trendy among highbrow conservatives. Sometimes it illuminates. But more often it just cloaks the writer’s disdain in metaphysical language. “Gnostic” functions, in this article, as an accusation: Progressives aren’t just wrong; they’re engaged in heresy. That might be rhetorically satisfying, but only if you don’t ask too many questions.\r\nAlso, the article conspicuously underplays the right-wing and reactionary forms of political religion. If we’re talking about salvation through politics, millenarianism, martyrdom, sacred violence, and the fusion of Caesar and God, we can’t just ignore contemporary Christian nationalism. Or militia movements, QAnon, replacement theory, Flight 93, and the cult of providential strongmen. You can’t plausibly use the Burned-over District to explain progressive fanaticism while ignoring right-wing movements entirely. Doran is making the typical polemical mistake of noticing the tendency he deplores only in people he dislikes.\r\nThe better point is broader and less partisan: Politics in America have always been vulnerable to religious transposition. But that’s not a uniquely progressive temptation. Nor is it a uniquely American phenomenon. \r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Second group of concerns—welcome your thoughts and commentary as time, energy and interest permit and possibly inspire. In no particular order.\r\nJimmy Lai.\r\nAI data centers\r\nGrade inflation at Harvard.\r\nRecent news on the “work” of the Southern Poverty Law Center\r\nKevin Warsh.\r\n—Russell-Dad Whiting [ https://substack.com/profile/6268785-russell-dad-whiting?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\nLet’s see. I’ll choose one. Why don’t we go with the Southern Poverty  Law Center? \r\nSubscribe, for the love of God!\r\nI don’t like the Southern Poverty Law Center. It treats perfectly legitimate views as if they were evidence of extremism; its ideological categories are sloppy, self-flattering, and defamatory. Ayaan Hirsi Ali’s treatment by the SPLC was a disgrace. \r\nBut the Trump administration’s legal campaign against it is outrageous. And Hirsi Ali’s applause for it is an equal and opposite disgrace. \r\nThe maneuver is now all too familiar. First, a senior official brandishes a sheaf of official-looking papers before the press corps. Then comes the solemn announcement that the documents prove a vast and sinister political conspiracy. The assumption—always sound, alas—is that no one will read them. The document has performed its function merely by existing. \r\nTulsi Gabbard did this with her Russiagate folder: Here, behold, proof that Barack Obama engineered a fiendish coup plot against Donald Trump. The documents, for anyone deranged enough to read them, proved no such thing. But the point was never proof. A folder was waved. Words were intoned. The desired audience received the desired conclusion.\r\nThe SPLC indictment is the same trick. In their press conference, Todd Blanche and Kash Patel accused the SPLC of “manufacturing the “extremism it purports to expose” and fueling “racial hatred” in the US.  “The SPLC is manufacturing racism to justify its existence,” said Blanche.\r\nThe casual consumer is meant to absorb the following story: The SPLC paid racists, therefore the racists were not real; the watchdog created the wolves; the anti-extremism industry invented extremism so better to fund itself. \r\nBut the indictment says nothing of the sort. [ https://substack.com/redirect/212877cb-d121-42a6-869d-da8ac4fe74ac?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ] It does not allege that paying informants is a crime. It could hardly do so, since the federal government itself pays informants with the enthusiasm of a Victorian philanthropist funding orphanages. The FBI, drug-enforcement agencies, counterterrorism units, police departments, shady journalists, private investigators, fraud examiners, and intelligence services all rely on sources, some of them unsavory. That is why they are useful. People with pristine moral hygiene are rarely embedded in neo-Nazi networks. They tend to be at farmers’ markets, selecting the least problematic radish.\r\nThe actual allegation is narrower: that the SPLC used fictitious entities and misleading bank paperwork to conceal payments to field sources. That may be a legal problem. If false statements were made to federally insured banks, if business records were falsified, if accounts were opened under sham entities with the intent to deceive, then the question belongs in court. Fine. Litigate it. But the leap from that allegation to “the SPLC invented white supremacy” is not an argument. It’s a propaganda hallucination.\r\nIndeed, the indictment’s own narrative depends on the reality of the extremist groups involved. It refers to the Klan, neo-Nazi networks, Aryan Nations affiliates, National Alliance circles, and Charlottesville-adjacent organizers. These aren’t figments summoned into being by direct mail. The administration wants to take the SPLC’s alleged use of sources inside extremist movements and turn it into evidence that the movements themselves were somehow fictive. By that logic, the FBI’s use of informants in organized crime would prove that the Mafia was invented by the Bureau.\r\nThe legal question is whether the SPLC concealed payments improperly. The political story you’re being sold is that white supremacy itself was a civil-rights fundraising scheme. Those are not the same proposition. They are not even close relatives. The difference is the difference between “the detective used informants” and “therefore the crime wave was staged by the detective.” \r\nThe donor-fraud theory is especially rich. We’re asked to imagine SPLC donors discovering, to their horror, that an organization they funded to monitor violent extremists had paid sources to penetrate violent extremist networks. One can picture the shock: “I gave money to help expose neo-Nazis, and you spent it finding out what neo-Nazis were doing?” \r\nThe government’s theory depends on a bizarre picture of what SPLC donors thought anti-extremism work consisted of: newsletters, seminars, earnest reports, perhaps a tote bag? Any serious donor to an organization monitoring violent extremist networks would surely understand that such work requires sources, infiltration, intelligence, and ugly contact with ugly people. That’s not a betrayal of the mission. It’s the mission. The notion that donors were defrauded because SPLC money was used to obtain intelligence from inside the movements SPLC existed to monitor is, shall we say, not the strongest limb on which the government has ever perched.\r\nElon Musk, as usual, has supplied the interpretive service for people who find reading too austere. His contribution is meme laundering: taking a narrow indictment about alleged bank-account concealment and converting it into the sweeping allegation that white supremacy was a manufactured civil-rights product. His role in this little pageant is to perform illiteracy at scale. The government waves an indictment; Musk reads the press release; the press release reads the political desire; and the desired conclusion is then blasted to hundreds of millions of people as if it had survived contact with the document.\r\nDonald Trump, of course, has derived the obvious and logical conclusion, as any rational man who is wholly fit to control our nuclear arsenal would:\r\nWhat makes the performance especially grotesque is that the SPLC worked with the FBI for years. The FBI evidently found the organization’s information useful until Kash Patel decided, in the new dispensation, that the real national-security threat was not extremist violence but the people who monitored it. This doesn’t immunize the SPLC from bank-fraud law. But it does make the theatrics somewhat difficult to swallow. Yesterday’s useful source network has become today’s sinister conspiracy, because the political weather changed.\r\nAgain: I don’t like the SPLC’s ideological habits. But the SPLC’s flaws aren’t a license for the government to manufacture a false story about them, and by implication civil-rights work itself. There’s a profound difference between saying, “This organization has sometimes smeared people unfairly,” and saying, “This organization invented white supremacy to fleece its donors.” \r\nThe administration gets away with these outrages because citizens don’t read.  They announce what the papers “prove,” then rely on repetition, tribal appetite, and the public’s learned helplessness before legal language. The indictment becomes an icon, and its contents are almost beside the point.\r\nThe SPLC may have questions to answer about paperwork, banking representations, and operational concealment. The administration has a different project: to persuade the public that the watchdog created the wolves. That’s not law: It is its opposite. And theater for the functionally unread.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Thanks for the official opportunity to ask this: What do you currently use to keep your cognitive apparatus in such brilliant form? Of course you research and reflect, read and reason ... I don’t mean those things. Rather, are you instructing advanced yoga? Is Davidzon helping you memorize key poems from the Russian canon? Me, I’m reviving my classical piano repertoire and teaching myself multi-variable calculus. \r\nCultivating diverse perceptual frameworks and the ability to move among them is foundational for generating the kind of exceptional product that you do. So— what is in your garden? \r\n—George Hawrysch [ https://substack.com/profile/8196947-george-hawrysch?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\nGeorge, I hesitate to divulge the full regimen, but since you ask: It is very simple. In infancy, I was placed on the standard JS Mill schedule, though my parents improved upon it by eliminating play. Greek began at eighteen months; Latin at two; moral philosophy at two and a half; and by three I was expected to produce a defensible position on the Corn Laws before being allowed a biscuit. \r\nAt four, I was allowed to use blocks to compare the Peloponnesian War with the War of the Spanish Succession. I was thereafter given the Russian canon, the Ricardian theory of rent, and a small harpsichord upon which I was permitted to express no emotion not previously authorized by Burke. At five, I was introduced to Ottoman tax farming, modal logic, and the works of Carlyle; I was soon enough started on Sanskrit—chiefly to prevent me from developing vulgar emotional attachments in English.\r\nThe piano was deemed too sensual, so I was assigned fugue analysis. Calculus was permitted only after breakfast, provided I had first declined five irregular Hebrew verbs and identified three errors in Gladstone.\r\nTo maintain the apparatus now, I rise before dawn to perform ten repetitions of “what is the category error here?” and fifteen minutes of source criticism. I  mentally prosecute three public figures, then enjoy  a cooling stretch in which I contemplate civilizational decay. Breakfast consists of coffee, a boiled egg, and three paragraphs of prose by someone both wrong and pleased with himself. I am bolstered by the invigorating discovery, renewed each morning, that the world is governed by men who would have struggled with the simpler passages of The Blue Book.\r\nAt midmorning I take my constitutional, arguing silently with Lacan, Saussure, or the latest American to mistake a character disorder for a theory of government. Luncheon is followed by a restorative period of resentment, ideally converted into prose before it becomes medical. In the afternoon, I rotate among perceptual frameworks: history, theology, strategy, and the study of power as exercised by people who should never have been allowed near a microphone. Davidzon is not, regrettably, drilling me in the Russian canon. (He is too preoccupied with his doomed love affairs.)\r\nAs for the garden: It is not so much a garden as an overeducated allotment. There are trained hedges of history, espaliered Renaissance shrubs, a poisonous patch of Middle Eastern acronyms that no known herbicide can kill, and several beds of resentment; there is a special plot reserved for Fungoids: strange growths, natural and wild, many-hued, exquisite, full of poisons, and privately printed. The poetry grows badly but survives neglect. The strategy section is overrun by despair. The literature bed is healthier, though Nabokov has strangled several smaller plants. In the corner, an Oxford shrub keeps muttering “define your terms.” \r\nCompost is essential. Into it go bad metaphors. With luck, by spring, some of it comes back as usable copy.\r\nI admire your piano and multivariable calculus. I may respond by taking up chess problems, or the fitted sheet, which remains the Everest of domestic topology. One does what one can.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Is cheese part of the CG remit? Why?\r\n—Tom Fleming\r\nYes. Yes. Cheese is emphatically part of the CG remit.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Can your bots collect the nuts of data discontinued, distorted and suppressed by the US government into some sort of comparison with such operations by other authoritarian states, like Russia? \r\n—Paul Janos\r\nPaul, I’m guessing—forgive me if I’m mistaken; if I am, tell me—that you mean to ask whether the AI tools to which I have access can gather the fragments of US government data that have been deleted, discontinued, altered, ideologically recoded, or made harder to access, and compare that pattern with the way authoritarian regimes such as Russia suppress or manipulate information. Is that correct? \r\nIf so, the answer is yes, but the comparison would need to be precise. The United States isn’t Russia. American public data systems are still monitored by courts, watchdogs, universities, archivists, journalists, state governments, FOIA litigation, and a large independent research ecosystem. But that, perhaps, is why the comparison is useful. Democratic decay doesn’t begin with a Ministry of Truth. It begins with broken links, changed definitions, missing baselines, politicized categories, chilled agencies (or agencies axed entirely), and statistical series that quietly stop being comparable over time.\r\nThere’s already a great deal to examine: the removal or alteration of federal climate, demographic, and public-health resources since 2025, for example, and the legal fights over restored health datasets. Librarians, researchers, and civic groups are scrambling to preserve endangered federal data.\r\nA CG piece could compare several mechanisms: deletion, category manipulation, funding strangulation, intimidation of expert agencies, replacement of neutral terminology with ideological language, uncertainty about official numbers, or the creation of rival official narratives. The Russian comparison would be useful not because the systems are identical, but because Russia shows the endpoint. Once public statistics become instruments of regime legitimacy, citizens no longer know whether they are reading information or state propaganda. \r\nMy guess is that you’d find that America is not much like Russia. But regimes like Russia’s illustrate the mature form of practices that begin, in democracies, with bureaucratic vandalism and ideological cleansing. I don’t know that AI would be necessary to conduct an inquiry like this. It would just take a lot of time, and a serious budget. \r\nThe US is not yet an authoritarian state. Most democracy indices consider it a flawed or partial democracy. The Economist’s 2025 Democracy Index [ https://substack.com/redirect/fec33d51-0b8f-4bbe-9306-0588482f6abd?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/3c9352b5-b4ae-42b0-892a-730945e98eda?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]assigned it a score of 7.65, which is below the 8.01 threshold for a full democracy, but nowhere near 3.99 (a score below that denotes an authoritarian regime). It has presumably sunk even more since then, but I doubt it’s even fallen into the “hybrid” category yet. It’s been in the “flawed” category, by the way, since 2016; since Trump’s re-election, it has fallen from 28th to 34th.\r\nThe difference between “flawed democracy” and “authoritarian regimes” is very significant. \r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: As I look at the problems of humanity, many (most?) seem of the multipolar trap variety. And, as the population careens toward ~10 billion, I think the only way to mitigate these traps is through stronger global institutions. (I’m just a dumb engineer, but I do have a lot of experience in control of complex, nonlinear systems—not unlike human ecosystems?) Do you agree? Is this possible? Are we doomed?\r\n—Blake Suhre [ https://substack.com/profile/18032714-blake-suhre?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\nBlake, by “multipolar trap,” do you mean problems that arise when multiple actors, each behaving rationally according to the incentives they face, produce collectively disastrous outcomes? I’m going to assume that you do, because as it happens, this kind of problem is, in my view, precisely the kind that most threatens humanity right now: Climate change, arms races,  AI competition, tax competition, pandemic failure, antibiotic resistance, migration pressure, cyber conflict, and perhaps even social-media epistemic collapse all have exactly this structure.\r\nSo I’ll assume you mean situations in which no single actor can solve the problem by behaving well, because each actor fears being punished for unilateral restraint. If one state decarbonizes while others free-ride, if one laboratory slows AI development while rivals accelerate, if one country maintains humane asylum rules while others dump the burden, if one platform refuses to permit inflammatory content while competitors monetize it, the system punishes virtue and rewards defection. I’ve written about this problem before:\r\nI’m instinctively sympathetic to the argument for stronger global institutions. This is not because I fondly imagine a benevolent world government issuing edicts from Geneva in immaculate sans serif—and even if I did, the phrase “world government” alone is enough to make half the planet reach for a rifle. I’m sympathetic to it because there’s no alternative. Many of our most urgent problems are beyond the capacity of the nation-state, acting alone, to solve. The great political dilemma of the twenty-first century is that the most serious dangers we face are planetary, but political legitimacy remains national—or even tribal.\r\nThe engineer’s analogy is useful. Human societies are complex, nonlinear, adaptive systems. They have feedback loops, time delays, tipping points, perverse incentives, cascading failures, and actors who learn how to game the control mechanism. But the analogy should serve as a caution against technocratic fantasy. You can’t control a political ecosystem the way you control a machine, because the components have beliefs, identities, resentments, memories, and lawyers. Any institution strong enough to solve global collective-action problems must also be constrained, lest it become a problem in its own right. \r\nSo, do I agree with you? Yes. Emphatically. We need stronger global coordination, stronger monitoring, stronger enforcement, and stronger capacity to produce public goods. In the upcoming US presidential campaign, I’ll be looking carefully to see which candidates understand this and say so. \r\nBut the phrase “global institutions” needs to be defined carefully. Sometimes this means formal treaties; sometimes clubs of major powers; sometimes standards bodies; sometimes insurance pools; sometimes data-sharing systems; sometimes scientific early-warning networks; sometimes sanctions regimes; sometimes boring institutions that nobody’s ever heard of but everyone depends on. \r\nThe tricky question isn’t whether we need stronger institutions (we do), but what kind of strength those institutions need—informational, legal, fiscal, coercive, technical, reputational, norm-setting? The World Health Organization, the International Atomic Energy Agency, the WTO, the IPCC, the Financial Stability Board, the Montreal Protocol regime, aviation safety systems, and nuclear nonproliferation architecture all exercise very different kinds of institutional power. Some work better than others, because the underlying incentive structure is different. Looking at the UN General Assembly will give you a good idea of what doesn’t work. \r\n“Stronger global institutions” has to mean mechanisms for escaping particular traps, designed specifically for the institution in question,  not vague paeans to multilateralism. Climate, AI, pandemics, migration, financial contagion, nuclear risk, and information warfare aren’t the same problem. They don’t solve identically. The world can’t be governed by one magnificent global parliament. It needs to be carefully patched by hundreds of partially overlapping regimes that make defection harder, cooperation cheaper, and catastrophic error less likely.\r\nLet’s consider an example that’s been at the forefront of my many preoccupations in recent years—AI risk. This is a textbook trap of the kind we’re discussing: enormous upside, strategic rivalry, private profit, military utility, opacity, speed, and a huge potential catastrophic downside. It’s a better pilot case than “global governance” in the abstract, because the relevant actors are (relatively) identifiable—frontier labs, major cloud providers, chipmakers, governments, militaries, standards bodies, and a finite number of research ecosystems.\r\nWe have no need for a vague Ministry of the Future to manage this problem. We need something like the IAEA. But it has to be adapted to a technology that’s  private, fast-moving, commercially valuable, and dual-use from inception. \r\nThe institution’s purpose should not be to “govern AI” in some vague Davos sense. It should be to govern frontier AI capabilities that create systemic risk, and as a first sketch, it probably ought to have four jobs:\r\nRegistration and monitoring. Any actor training or deploying frontier models above a defined compute, capability, or autonomy threshold would have to register them. That includes model architecture basics, training compute, major datasets at a high level, safety evaluations, deployment context, and incident reporting.\r\nEvaluation and licensing. Systems wouldn’t be deployable just because a company built them. They would require pre-deployment testing by accredited evaluators or by the institution itself, looking especially at the potential for cyberattacks, autonomous replication, biological-design assistance, persuasion or manipulation at scale, weapons integration, and loss-of-control indicators.\r\nTracking compliance. Because models are hard to see but large-scale compute is visible, the institution should monitor the supply chain for advanced chips and high-end cloud clusters—the AI equivalent of watching fissile material. This is an imperfect way to do it, but much more feasible than watching every line of code.\r\nEmergency coordination. The institution would maintain a crisis mechanism in the event of dangerous capability breakthroughs, leaks of frontier weights, autonomous agent failures, or evidence of state or military misuse.\r\nThe closest analogue would be the IAEA, which offers a model for the way it could conduct inspections, establish safeguards, and verify that dangerous capabilities aren’t being diverted into prohibited uses. It could also resemble the Financial Stability Board, in that it would identify institutions whose failure or recklessness could endanger the whole system, or the International Civil Aviation Organization, which sets technical standards in a way that might be worth emulating (states retain sovereignty, but common standards make the system safer). And it could be modeled on the OPCW, too, which declares whole categories of weapons beyond the limits of international tolerance, and the IPCC, in that it would issue periodic, authoritative, consensus statements about risk.\r\nThe institution I have in mind would have to borrow from all of them. No single template already exists, because AI isn’t just an industry, but it isn’t quite a weapon, isn’t quite infrastructure, isn’t quite speech, and isn’t quite a scientific field. It’s all of them. \r\nThe hard part, as always, is legitimacy. A global AI regulator would immediately face objections. The US will be afraid of constraining its own firms while China races ahead.. China will fear that AI safety is a disguise for American technological containment. Companies will fear losing trade secrets and the advantage of speed. The rest of the world will fear being permanently locked out of a technology developed elsewhere and then regulated by those who already have it. \r\nSo this institution would need a bargain at its core, a bit like the bargain that made the NPT successful. (Reasonably. So far.) Access to the frontier AI ecosystem comes with obligations: disclosure, testing, incident reporting, liability, and compliance. In return, states and firms gain legitimacy, access to shared science, protections like insurance, compute markets, and maybe preferential access to certified models. This part really matters. A regulator that only says “no” will be evaded. A regulator that genuinely creates a safer, more trusted market will be seen as useful.\r\nWhat would “strength” mean in this context, then? Not world government, obviously. It wouldn’t mean blue-helmeted AI inspectors kicking down the door at Anthropic. It would mean that the organization has the following capabilities: \r\nEyes: The institution is able to see where the biggest training runs and deployments are happening.\r\nStandards: It defines common testing protocols for dangerous capabilities.\r\nVerification: It has the power to audit claims, inspect facilities, and demand access to the logs.\r\nLeverage: It can deny access to chips, cloud compute, public contracts, insurance, and international deployment permissions.\r\nSpeed: It has emergency powers to convene governments and labs during an incident.\r\nPublic trust: It publishes enough to make the world less dependent on corporate self-certification.\r\nAre we doomed? I don’t know. We have a very dangerous institutional lag. Our problems have globalized faster than our capacity to govern them. The optimistic case is that humans have repeatedly built institutions after discovering that unmanaged competition was intolerable (central banks, public-health systems, arms-control regimes, aviation rules, maritime law, nuclear hotlines, ozone agreements). The pessimistic case is that we tend to build them only after catastrophe has done the teaching. We have to learn before the exam is administered with live ammunition. \r\nAlso, the power that would once have naturally led the campaign to create these institutions—the United States—has gone berserk. I don’t know if it retains the capacity for rational behavior. It certainly no longer has the moral authority that leading other countries requires. Americans are now profoundly hostile to international institutions of any stripe. In some cases, the hostility is well warranted (see: UN Human Rights Council [ https://substack.com/redirect/f15b2c41-7b41-44b9-bc6b-953bbceca8cd?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]). In others, it’s absurd. \r\nFurthermore, to use the example of my hypothetical AI-regulation institution, our tech companies are now more powerful than our government. They are led by psychopaths who will spare no expense to avoid being regulated. I don’t know if you’ve heard this story, which I learned about from Ezra Klein’s podcast: [ https://substack.com/redirect/8bcbb28c-0d88-4018-859a-13b87f2d54cf?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/656d8938-871f-4da7-b3cf-d2789f539d7f?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]\r\nKlein: If you are living in New York’s 12th Congressional District, you may have seen these endless attacks on Alex Bores, one of the Democrats running there.\r\nSinister voiceover from the attack ad: … He made hundreds of thousands of dollars building and selling the tech for ICE, enabling ICE and powering their deportations while making bank. Now he’s running from his past. ICE is powered by Bores’ tech.\r\nKlein: Yikes. Bores did work for Palantir. The rest of that attack is not what you might call true. But what interests me is who is paying for it. The Super PAC Leading the Future, and its subsidiary, ThinkBig. Who funds the Super PAC Leading the Future?\r\nWell, among their big donors are co-founders of OpenAI, Andreessen Horowitz, and wait for it … Palantir. \r\nSo why is a co-founder of Palantir—Joe Lonsdale, in this case—funding a Super PAC to try to destroy a candidate on the grounds that he once worked for Palantir? The reason is Leading the Future is a Super PAC dedicated to destroying anyone who might regulate the tech industry in general, or AI specifically, in a way these funders don’t like.\r\nAnd Bores, as a member of the New York State Assembly, co-authored and passed the RAISE Act, one of the first pieces of AI regulation passed in any major state. There is a principle here that is much more important than any single congressional seat. You’ll hear it, honestly, if you just listen to AI founders talk.\r\nThey say they believe in it. Sam Altman, a co-founder of OpenAI—who, it should be said, has been horribly targeted in recent violent attacks by anti-AI individuals—he was trying to cool down temperatures here, writing, “It is important that the democratic process remains more powerful than companies.” \r\nIt is important that the democratic process remains more powerful than companies. Altman is right. But it’s his co-founder, Greg Brockman, who is one of the major donors for Leading the Future, who is trying to make sure the democratic process is subordinate to the companies and is trying to do it by funding a super PAC that can unleash enough money to crush any legislators who cross them. \r\nCan you imagine what they’d do to a candidate who proposed creating the agency I have in mind? The agency we absolutely need, if we’re to survive this century?\r\nI pray that we come to our senses quickly, that China proves to be a more benevolent and farsighted global leader than it has been so far, or that the EU steps up to the plate. (I don’t see the initiative coming from any other source, do you?) \r\nBut I fear that if this fails to happen, then yes, we’re doomed.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Your series of articles, “The New Caesars,” came out a few years ago. How does the world score now compared to then, and how is our trajectory?\r\nI see some areas where the status quo seems relatively unchanged and entrenched illiberal leaders remain: Russia, China, Turkey, etc. Some areas where I have some tentative optimism: fall of Assad, fall of the Ayatollah, decimation of Iran’s proxy network.\r\nSome democratic results that seem promising (some, like Orban’s defeat seem very promising!): Orban’s defeat, DPP victory in Taiwan, the 2024 French snap election debacle\r\nAreas where I still have concerns: ongoing Ukraine war, election of Trump.\r\nThings I am not sure how to interpret: lots of South American issues, Bolsanaro’s Jan 6th and subsequent arrest, whatever is happening in Venezuela, Bukele and El Salvador, Milei and Argentina, Mark Carney’s victory\r\nMy results seem too positive, and I am sure I have miscategorized several. What is your assessment of where we are at?\r\n—Vints\r\nHi Vints!\r\nFor newcomers, he’s referring to these articles:\r\nAnd here’s a podcast to go with it:\r\nAs for your question, I don’t think it makes sense to grade the world by headline-events alone. You’ve done something intelligent by sorting events into authoritarian persistence, democratic rebound, and ambiguous cases, but you’re counting “autocrat fell” as “democracy improved,” and they aren’t the same thing. The fall of a tyrant may be an opening, but it isn’t institutions—not yet, anyway.\r\nGlobally, liberal democracy remains in its long recession. (I use the term “recession” because this is the term favored by political scientists and the media, but I dislike it, because it suggests that this is a phenomenon similar to an economic recession: cyclical, and highly likely to abate with time. Perhaps. But we don’t know yet.)  The world as a whole still looks grim. Freedom House records the twentieth consecutive year of decline in global freedom, and V-Dem’s 2026 report—which Dan and I discussed on a recent episode of Critical Conditions [ https://substack.com/redirect/3679aedd-c403-47eb-8a78-635fb092cf5c?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]—reports that only 18 countries, about 10 percent of the nations of the world, are  democratizing. Nearly a quarter are autocratizing.\r\nThe picture isn’t flat-out catastrophic. The EIU’s 2025 Democracy Index is more cautiously positive. After eight years of decline, their democracy scores stabilized in 2025. So the story may be changing from uniform democratic retreat to violent sorting: Some systems are hardening into autocracy; others are developing antibodies. \r\nThe world looks pretty grim, in the aggregate. It looks more polarized. Autocracies are more openly autocratic, democracies are more anxious, and some societies may be showing that democratic erosion is reversible.\r\nI think your list is too positive, but only because you treat every authoritarian setback as a democratic gain. I would distinguish sharply between “weakened autocrat” and “strengthened democracy.” Assad’s fall, for example, is unquestionably good if the comparison is with Assad. But Syria’s post-Assad condition is not democratic. It has improved from a catastrophically low base, but the institutional questions remain unresolved. \r\nEven more so for Iran. Khamenei’s death and the regime’s evident crisis are hardly the same as the fall of the Islamic Republic. The regime continues to repress brutally; it is on an unbearable execution spree—I can hardly bear to look at the faces of the young, beautiful people it is executing every day. Nothing, so far, suggests it’s experiencing a democratic transition. \r\nSo the category you want here is “authoritarian rupture,” not democratic consolidation. Hopeful openings don’t count as victories for liberal democracy until power is actually constrained, succession is regularized, coercive institutions are subordinated, and the opposition can organize without being murdered. The fall of an autocrat is the end of an era, not the beginning of a constitution.\r\nBut you’re right to note the bright spots. Hungary really matters. Orbán’s defeat is a major case because it shows that electoral-authoritarian systems, even paradigmatic ones, can still be beaten electorally; what’s more, the new government has a clear mandate to restore the rule of law. So I’m optimistic with you,, but let’s see where Hungary is a year from now. \r\nYes, Taiwan and Canada belong in the positive column, but let’s not exaggerate. The 2024 election showed that Taiwan’s democracy is resilient even under intense pressure from Beijing. But that’s what we’d expect to see, isn’t it? It’s a sign of how far our standards have fallen that we get excited when a mature, long-consolidated democracy holds a peaceful, free, and fair election. The same is true of Canada’s election. Canada isn’t an autocracy in need of rescue. We expect to see free and fair elections in Canada. So I’m glad that Taiwan and Canada are still capable of transferring power peacefully, but the fact of it doesn’t mean liberal democracy is winning, it just means the fire hasn’t consumed every country on the planet, thank God.\r\nBrazil should be in the “cautiously positive” column. Bolsonaro’s conviction is a very significant example. We can only admire it. His effort to stage a coup wasn’t just inspired by January 6, it was organized by the same people. (I wrote about this here, and I wish it had attracted more attention, because the story is outrageous.) \r\nBut I qualify my enthusiasm with the word “cautious” because Brazil’s democracy required the courts to defend it. Judicial defense of democracy is absolutely necessary in emergencies, but democracies can’t live forever on judicial heroics. Eventually, political parties and voters have to do the work. \r\nThe Latin American cases you wonder about are why it’s probably best to avoid easy categorizations. Bukele represents a paradigmatic order-versus-liberty problem. The collapse of the homicide rate in El Salvador is real (although some claim, plausibly to my ear, that the figures are exaggerated). So is the mass detention architecture and the prolonged state of exception. No one should celebrate the latter. But no one celebrated El Salvador’s homicide rate, either. I don’t see this as a standard case: I find it perfectly natural that people ceased to care about the niceties of due process and the rule of law when the state was failing so spectacularly at a states’s foremost responsibility—providing security. I’ve never fully understood why El Salvador became so violent, but if your homicide rate is 106.3 per 100,000 people, you can expect people to become mighty authoritarian.\r\nMilei is different. Argentina is a competitive democracy. Freedom House gives it good scores for a lively media, civil society, and public debate. (V-Dem’s 2026 report is concerned: It claims there have been attacks on freedom of expression, media freedom, and civil society.) I have to confess that my knowledge of Argentina is very superficial, so I would ask an Argentine what’s going on down there. \r\nOverall, the world is doing worse than I’d hoped, and better than I feared, but the United States is doing so badly that I can’t feel much optimism. Some countries matter more than others. Unless we end our authoritarian experiment and do so decisively, I fear that liberal democracy has no long-term hope anywhere. We’ve gone from being the guarantor of the liberal order to a state sponsor of democratic erosion, and a very powerful one. There’s a limit to how long the world’s liberal democracies can hold out when the most powerful countries in the world are working, simultaneously, to undermine them. You don’t need to accept V-Dem’s index numbers as inerrant to see the strategic implications of the US becoming an autocratizing basket case. The world’s liberal-democratic ecosystem has lost its greatest exemplar and its stabilizer. \r\nMore bad news: The autocrats have learned. They rarely abolish elections outright. They degrade the media, intimidate civil society, capture courts, politicize statistics, corrupt procurement, weaponize migration, and turn democratic procedure into scenery. \r\nThe good news is that societies have learned too. Voters can recognize the script earlier; courts sometimes hold; civil society preserves memories; and international pressure can matter.\r\nSo my assessment isn’t “we’re winning” or “we’re doomed.” It’s that the age of the New Caesars has entered a more dangerous but more interesting phase. Caesarism is no longer advancing everywhere unopposed. It’s meeting resistance. But resistance isn’t the same as victory, and victory isn’t the same as reconstruction. The biggest question now is whether anti-authoritarian coalitions can move from saying “no” to building institutions that make the next Caesar harder to produce. \r\nThe Caesars are no longer marching unimpeded. Some have stumbled; a few have fallen. But the factory that produces them is still open.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: The physical bases of le Universe seem wavy and cyclic. Is political/economic history also? If so, is not evolution incompatibly linear (progressive) in comparison, particularly as it achieves AI liftoff? Does evolution not, in its apex phase, attack—perhaps destroy—the helix of history itself?\r\n[I’m] suggesting that the progression of technology under the barbaric banner of biological (compete till death) evolution, gets back to the balances of Eden (virtually impossible) or—likely—carries on till earth is either desert or fields of glass; hence ending “historic” cycles. You must have some sort of cycles theory underpinning your Weltanschauung. The question is how resilient you believe cyclic permanence to be in the face of the dire threat of the acceleratingly apex animal.\r\n—Paul Janos\r\nHi Paul! \r\nI think you’re asking whether political history is cyclical, whether technological evolution is linear, and whether AI breaks the old cycle by giving cyclical human beings irreversible powers. Is that right? If so, my answer is: yes, that is one of the central dangers. Human passions recur; technology accumulates. We keep replaying old dramas with more powerful tools.\r\nI don’t ascribe to a simple cyclical theory of history, though I understand the attraction of one. Political history plainly has recurring forms: oligarchy, demagogy, imperial overstretch, revolution, decadence, reform, restoration, war, exhaustion, renewal. Everything’s a footnote to Plato.\r\nBut technology isn't cyclical in the same way, because it accumulates. Human beings stay recognizably human, but the instruments available to human folly become more powerful. That’s why I would never say history is a circle. It’s closer, as you point out, to a helix: recurring human patterns under conditions of increasing technical capacity. \r\nPolitics is cyclical because human passions are recurrent; technology is cumulative because knowledge compounds. The crisis of modernity (an inherently pretentious phrase, but what can I do, that’s what it is) is the collision between those two facts. We keep reenacting ancient dramas—fear, pride, rivalry, resentment, utopianism, greed—but with instruments of ever-increasing power. So I think your premise is partly right. The same patterns recur, but at higher energy levels, so to speak. \r\nAI matters because it may raise the energy level so dramatically that the old mechanisms of correction—defeat, embarrassment, bankruptcy, institutional reform—come too late. Institutions evolved for human-speed politics may be overwhelmed by machine-speed finance, propaganda, warfare, surveillance, and scientific discovery. If the old cycle was ambition, overreach, collapse, recovery, the new danger is unrecoverable overreach.\r\nSo I take your question very seriously. It’s at the center of most of what I write about these days. We may have finally built tools powerful enough to destroy the ecological and political conditions under which, previously, civilization renewed itself after episodic catastrophes. \r\nStill, I’d resist the fatalism. As I often say, you mitigate existential risk the same way you mitigate any other risk: by being more careful. I said it here, for example:\r\nOur species has built restraints before: law, taboos, arms control, constitutionalism, scientific norms, insurance, central banks, public health, aviation safety, nuclear command protocols. We can do it. But can we build new institutions fast enough to keep cumulative technology from turning recurrent human stupidity into terminal human stupidity? That’s the question. \r\nThe phrase “biological evolution” is, I think, doing too much work in your formulation. Evolution isn’t a command to “compete till death.” It also produces cooperation, kinship, reciprocity, symbiosis, restraint, and social intelligence. The problem isn’t evolution as such. The problem is that human beings evolved under conditions radically unlike those created by modern technology, and we’re not well-made for a world bursting with nuclear weapons, viral engineering, algorithmic propaganda, and artificial superintelligence. We have Stone Age threat responses and tribal cognition. Now, we have godlike instruments. A regrettable product launch.\r\nThe alternatives aren’t necessarily “Eden or glass.” Eden isn’t coming back. Annihilation isn’t inevitable. There’s a plausible future somewhere between paradise and vitrification: a long, dangerous struggle to domesticate our own capabilities. If we succeed in building sufficiently robust institutions, perhaps we can keep our ancient primate impulses from using modern tools to turn the planet into a memorial to our cleverness. \r\nWe should certainly try.\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nThe questions below are related—or at least, I relate them in my reply—so I’ve answered them separately. I’ll send that answer tomorrow. \r\nQUESTION: I’m gonna ask you the hardest question possible right now. I’m an Iranian (expat) and I worry about Iran’s future tremendously. How do you see this current crisis playing out for the Iranian people? Are there any hopes for a free Iran that is also not completely destroyed?\r\n—Alireza\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: How can society best deal with the crisis of antisemitism? Is this the new reality? How much worse can it get?\r\nSeparately, as a parent of three children, how can one best prepare them for media literacy/misinformation?\r\n—Huxbnw [ https://substack.com/profile/843098-huxbnw?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: So many points that I’ve considered and hoped that you, in one way or another, might address. Context: This article by Rich Lowry: [ https://substack.com/redirect/60d5eab0-61af-4adf-8d0c-2dca142499d6?j=eyJ1IjoiMWllZnkifQ.sG3OqnkHDNZpplC0eLA9u0NYhAE4J8yHwSPDyeVA8k8 ]\r\nWe are witnessing the rise of the Dearborn Democrats, not in the literal sense, but in the same sense that Jeanne Kirkpatrick coined the phrase “San Francisco Democrats” in the 1980s. Back then, San Francisco, an elite coastal city, stood for the dovishness and permissiveness of liberalism; today, Dearborn, home to a large Arab-American enclave, stands for an all-consuming opposition to Israel with all that that entails, including a conspiratorial view of AIPAC and an underlying anti-Westernism.\r\nThe ethos of the 2024 “uncommitted movement” in Michigan, urging voters not to vote for Joe Biden in protest of his support for the Gaza war, has now surged to a formidable position within the Democratic Party. A new Decision Desk poll shows that 75 percent of Democrats favor the Palestinians over the Israelis. The swing against Israel is even more pronounced among young voters. An Echelon Insights survey found that among Democrats under age 50, 54 percent had an unfavorable view of Iran, while 62 percent had an unfavorable view of Israel. \r\nConcerns on your end, Claire? Thank you.\r\n—Russell-Dad Whiting [ https://substack.com/profile/6268785-russell-dad-whiting?utm_source=substack-feed-item ]\r\n☋⚜️🌏⚜️☋⚜️🌍⚜️☋⚜️🌎⚜️☋\r\nQUESTION: Some background: if anyone asks me what I think about Israel/Palestine, I quote Isaac Deutscher: After WWII the Jews of Europe jumped out of a burning building and landed on the Palestinians. So my question now is: what about the settlers in the West Bank? (As for how Israel is waging war in Gaza and Lebanon, I don’t know what to believe re purported atrocities, although given it’s Netanyahu running things, I wouldn’t rule them out categorically.)\r\n—Doug1943\r\nPhew. \r\nAny further questions? \r\n—C.\r\n\r\nUnsubscribe https://substack..KEN_EEEOA4uspS0ygNlqZPL9DeUgHyZdEppxDzQ7aVU?",
